<br>
But on another note, I've been thinking-why go Orion-class?  A gas core NTR can get you cleaner and safer propulsion, and provide the function of a power plant, which can be useful if you use the same reactor on another planet, when you land.<br>
<br>
An NTR is far less risky in the atmosphere, if you design it correctly.  You can have a single stage orbiter, or even a single stage interplanetary craft, which uses the spent tanks as hab modules.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tim1965>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 135<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/19/03 1:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=301.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Orion Starship for non relatavistic crewed starfligh</span><hr size=1> Nuclear thermal rockets, and gas core nuclear rockets can not go fast enough for a practical interstellar space flight<br>
of any kind , other then an interstellar percuser mission.<br>
